No region cuts deeper into Kowloon's memory than the Cinderteeth. The Ashfall Monsoon shaped every institution the city has.
The Ashfall was not a single event. Three years of black volcanic rain choked canals, collapsed roofs, and turned fresh water to sulfur. Kowloon's low, wet, sky-open delta caught the worst. Ash mixed with rain became poison in every channel of the Shallow Thousand.
The Temple Circle maintains the Ashfall Registry: six hundred named dead from Yen-Mak, plus uncounted dead from years one and two. During the annual Ashfall Vigil, names are spoken aloud in darkness. The Executioner strikes the covenant stone three times. This is practice against forgetting, not ceremony.
The Jade Magistracy funds observers at the Chalkwind Saddles who report tremor frequency and gas color. Kowloon respects the Ventspeakers' practical geology. When the Ash Cult claims divine verdicts, the Temple Circle replies: "Verdicts do not drown children."
The Spirebound Conclave abandoned resonance crystals in the Bellspine ridge. The Courier Lantern Office classifies this as institutional negligence: instruments left running without keepers, potentially amplifying the seismic coupling that drove the Ashfall.
Kowloon adopted mountain Hazard Doctrine for harbor emergency codes. Silent Bell Protocol and double-water doctrine map to bay-bell patterns. When dock bells ring a certain way, every crew knows: stop, separate, do not share water.
Six subregions in the hazard registry: Ember Crown (active calderas), Bellspine (abandoned crystals ring), Chalkwind Saddles (observer posts), Glasswash Fans (obsidian and sulfur), Blackstep Footholds (mountain meets civic law), Western Fold (smoldering Conclave ruins).
The deep fault runs beneath the continent. The Jade Magistracy's standing order: watch the mountains, always.
