The Cinderteeth destroyed Rakuen's founding vision. Every child learns the Ash-and-Iron before the Paradise Thesis. You must know what killed the orchards before understanding what they meant.
The Ashfall settled into Rakuen's cisterns. Elys Savan's cooperative waterworks, pride of the Southward Compact, became poison delivery systems. Orchards that fed three generations choked on sulfur rain. The Festival of Ever-Bloom was cancelled for the first time. The Ash Requiem is sung each anniversary at the Bloom Pavilion.
The Spirebound Conclave's abandoned resonance crystals in the Bellspine meant no monitoring, no warning. The Ventspeakers who read volcanic behavior as practical geology had already been displaced by institutions that valued measurement over listening.
The Garden Ledger Clerks keep a sealed jar of ash beside pressed flowers of the last full bloom. The contrast is the lesson: what was grown, and what fell from the sky to kill it.
During the Ash-and-Iron decades, Rakuen adopted ration towers, labor drafts, and salvage courts. Every mechanism the Paradise Thesis rejected became necessary for survival. The city became what it was founded to refuse.
The Ash Cult claims divine verdict. The Ember Wardens read it differently: the mountains do not judge, they burn. Judgment belongs to those who knew the ash would fall and chose not to warn, and those who watched the cisterns darken and offered refusal instead of aid.
The Cracked Promise Stones nearest the mountain road bear the deepest fractures. The Ember Wardens say the cracks point toward the Cinderteeth. The Garden Ledger Clerks say they point toward Midgaard. Both are correct. Ash came from one direction. Abandonment from the other.
